segments.text: We're back in business.
Okay.
So we were talking about just your general view on war prior to the war.
Okay.
After I got into it and saw what it was, I guess as far as killing, it came more of second nature to me.
I just did it, and I didn't think about it.

After basically, you know, you're sitting there watching the guy beside you get blown away or, you know, there's bombs hitting all around your mortars or whatever, you're sitting there shooting or you're keeping your head down or whatever just to stay alive.
So you're fighting for your own life.
And you really don't think about what you're fighting for other than your own personal salvation to stay alive.
You...
Get very close to God if you're a religious person.
You pray a lot.
You know, you promise everybody in the world everything if you can come out of it alive type thing.
Yeah, you get in a situation like that, it's hard to really express your feelings until you've gotten there.
But once you're there and you're in it, you know, you really wake up to really what the world's all about.
And you appreciate God.

things in life that you probably would have never even thought were there or realized like running water or flush toilets or whatever you want to say I mean you know that sort of thing but the war part of it as far as killing I feel you know they taught me how to kill that was one thing I learned and to me it's second nature not that I'm going to go out and kill anybody tomorrow or nothing but I could probably see somebody killed and or
kill somebody and I wouldn't think twice about it.
I'm very numb to that.
I have no feelings that way.
I'm very numb.
And I had to blame the Vietnam War on that.
If I was called upon to go fight again, which I probably never will be, I probably would do it without even thinking.
You know, not that I'm quote 100% patriot or anything like that, but it's just that maybe that's in me.
I don't know.
It's been described by...

Well, like, for example, Philip Caputo with the First Marines, he said even though he was an anti-war protester, after he got out of Vietnam, he said there was still that attraction in him about Vietnam, and he could not deny that for what it was worth.
There was something about the camaraderie that none of us who have never been to war could ever realize.
You try to explain it to your family or wife or friends or anybody, especially if a relative dies or something.
I have had several close relatives die and friends, and I show no emotion to it.
Do you feel any emotion?
I really don't.
Maybe someday it will hit me.
I don't know.
But at this stage of the game, since I've been back, I've been very numb to death.
And, you know, I have been in incidents where, with my job especially here, these guys got killed in that car accident, and I found them in the water dead.

And, you know, I personally found them and, you know, helped pull them out of the water and everything, and it didn't affect me at all, although there was people all around just screaming and crying and yelling and everything because these guys were dead.
But to me, it didn't affect me whatsoever.
I'd seen so much death and blood that it didn't bother me.
And so, in a way, I guess that is what war means to me.
You know, I have no feelings.
I'm very numb.
Do you?
Exactly.
Any more?
Do you feel like you have any illusions?
No, no.
I had, initially, when I came back, it was really tough.
I was very jumpy and, you know, people couldn't come near me while I was sleeping.
I've slept very, very lightly.
I had a real hard time adjusting initially the first year or so.
I was back, it was tough, and I was very violent.
Basically, I would, you know, if somebody upset me, I would just go into a rage sometimes.
And you've probably experienced that when you were working with me.
I, since, I guess the last two years, have really mellowed out from that standpoint.
But it took me quite a few years to really get over that.
Do loud noises make you jumpy?
Very jumpy, yes.
Even to this day, if I hear a gunshot, my first reaction is to get down.
I mean, very, very quick.
It's ingrained in you, isn't it?
Yes.
And I initially did not hunt for several years after I got back, but I did get back into hunting again in the woods and shooting again, deer hunting, duck hunting, whatever that way.
And I found it very, very second nature.
to go back out into the woods again and hunt.
And I was able, actually I've shot more deer probably since then because maybe of my training in the war, you know, that way.
It's just nothing to go out and pop a deer and, you know, be able to see it and hit it and know what's there, you know, that sort of thing.
See through the camouflage.
See through what's there, exactly.
Do you catch yourself looking for tripwires whenever you go to the jungle?
Well, I look for anything.
And not necessarily tripwires, but there's things that I'll be walking along and I sit there and say, stop, or something.
There's a guy with me.
What the hell are you doing?
And I said, see that over there?
There's an animal in there or something.
And you can just see things.
And the guy says, what are you talking about?
And I said, right there.
See that?
Yeah, you see different footprints, and you can tell, especially where the deer, when you're deer hunting, I guess it's more prevalent than anything else.
You can see where they've been and track them and follow them and see where the animals were.
But the actual sense that's there, I don't know what you call it, seven cents there again, but I really have got that still.
I think in the woods I could be very, very pleased to go back out in the jungle and live if I had to.
Thanks.
That's pretty interesting.
You're not the only one that's stated that.
While we're on the subject of your homecoming, what was your homecoming like?
Did the military ship you back and then just dump you in Houston, Texas and say you're home?
Was there any adjustment period?
No, there was no adjustment period.
I had a very unique homecoming.
My unit did stand down the 101st.
I'm sorry, not the 101st, the 1st Cav.
The 101st stood down, too, but I came home with the first cab.
It was the second of the fifth, which basically was just our particular unit.
So you did come back with the unit?
Well, not actually.
I came home, and they stood down two weeks later.
So I flew back from Vietnam to Travis Air Force Base, went through debriefing at Travis Air Force Base, stayed there for almost two weeks.

And they basically every day would question me and debrief me and check me and test my urine and all this sort of thing, make sure I was drug free and that I wasn't a sicko and I wasn't going to go blow people away and all this sort of thing.
So there was about a two-week debriefing period where I could not see anyone or talk to anyone.
I couldn't even call my family.
And I was in the States, but I couldn't call or talk to them for two weeks.
you know, was kind of getting back familiar with the world, they called it.
I came back to the world.
And I was still in the military at the time, and I supposedly had two more months to go before I was out.
So what they decided to do with me would be to go ahead and give me an early out so I didn't have to do any service because I wasn't going to re-up.
And they tried their best in that two-week period to get me to sign up for more time, but I didn't do it.
And...
So they went ahead and gave me an early out at that time, and the unit stood down at Fort Hood, Texas.

So I came home to Pasadena, and when the unit came home to Fort Hood, I went back up to Fort Hood, and they actually had a major ceremony with the band and the whole nine yards for the colonels and the captains and everybody, and they went through the whole deal and had a big cake and party on the lawn.
for the unit standing down and coming home from Vietnam.
And the colonels and everybody that I'd worked with was there.
So it was pretty emotional because they all left like two weeks after I did and came home.
So I came home basically, got my wife and immediately drove to Fort Hood, Texas and met them there.
And so I got to see the guys and everybody I was with and everything.
And the majority of them were still in the service and stationed at Fort Hood at that time.
Did y'all party like hell that night?
Yeah, we had a pretty good time.
We really enjoyed it.
Actually, I was with my wife again at the same time with the guys I'd been with for six months, too.
It was getting to know the stateside plus my wife, that sort of thing.
It was pretty emotional all the way around.
They got to meet her.
Of course, you always talk about your family and stuff with your buddies, that sort of thing.
Then we went back home and I
tried not to go back to work, but I couldn't stay around the house.
I had to go and do, so I went back to work pretty quick.
Was it easy to find a job?
Well, I already had the job.
I was very fortunate there.

When I left and was drafted, I was working for Exxon, and Exxon basically paid my wife dependency pay the whole time I was in NOM, and so when I came back, I was guaranteed a job, so I walked right back into the job at Exxon, and I
basically got my seniority back.
My job was right there waiting for me and everything, so it was no problem to walk right back into a job at all.
It was hard to get used to the routine again, but I was able to go back into it.
Did you ever receive any abuse for being a back?
No abuse, but I did expect to be... Down upon maybe?
No, not really.
I expected to be treated more as a hero.
because I came back alive and well, but I was never really treated one way or the other.
It was no, it was like, oh, you went to NAMM?
Big deal, you know.
And I said, Jesus, I went over there and fought for the country and almost died and, you know, all this, all that.
I come back and it's no big deal, you know.
And, you know, that's really the way it was.
I got no special treatment, no preference treatment, you know,
No real thank you or nothing, you know, from anybody.
And, of course, my military benefits as far as my schooling and housing and stuff like that were all there, my VA benefits.
But that's really the only thing that really came out of the whole deal, you know, after the fact, so to speak.
Do you think if you didn't have this, I don't mean to use the word party, but this party, so to say, this get-together with the First Cap back at Fort Hood.
Mm-hmm.
Do you think if you didn't at least have that bit of a welcome back committee, do you think it would have been a hell of a lot worse for you personally?
Probably so.
Emotionally?
Probably so.
And, you know, of course, my family treated me like I was a hero.
I mean, that was, I can say, but no one outside my family ever did.
And...
You know, I'm sure all the veterans feel the same way.
This is pretty much a standard deal across the board.
They got just slided by everybody.
And, you know, just until the recent time, you know, the veterans hadn't even hardly been acknowledged to be in there.
And, you know, just in the recent, you know, years, past few years, if, you know, anybody, you know, the Congress or, you know, the President or anybody really acknowledged that,
There was a war, or there was veterans, or people did die, you know, this sort of thing.
So that, I think, if anything, is very, very hard to swallow because thousands and thousands of guys and girls lost their lives in Nam.
And, you know, it's something that should be remembered and, you know, respected for those that did fight and did come back and did die.
And, you know, just until here recently, that hasn't happened.
What do you think about when you got back?
Were there any anti-war protests?
No, I didn't see anything like that.
That really never bothered me.
I saw a lot of it before I went.
What about afterwards?
Afterwards, never really saw anything that much directly at all.
I saw a lot of it on TV.
What did you think about it when you saw it on TV?
It didn't really bother me because I had a choice to make, too.
I could have tried to dodge a draft.
I could have gone to Canada.
I could have.
When AWOL, I had choices too.
I could have stayed in school and not got drafted.
I mean, you know, it's a situation.
I guess I chose my own destiny in a way.
Going back to my basic training, my AIT, the guys that came out of AIT, there was only about six of us that ended up going to NAM out of about 50 of us.
Everybody else went to Germany.
So, you know, it's a weird situation.
There's still two or three guys that I went in with that were local here in the Houston area.
One guy lives in Alvin.
I see him every once in a while.
He went to Germany for the whole two-year stint.
He had a house in Germany where he was living off base.
He had a blast over there.
He bought some German cars and Mercedes and stuff like that.
The guy had a blast while he was there.
Here I was in Vietnam getting shot at.
I felt that I accepted what they gave me and I did it the way I wanted to do it.
I had a choice.
And I chose it and did the best I could with it.
So the protest and stuff and the anti-war stuff, you know, that's an individual type thing.
I have no problem with that at all.
I've heard this from some veterans, one particular, the helicopter pilot that I talked to you earlier about.
What he stated when he got back, one, he had no readjustment period whatsoever.
Right.
Personally, this can be two-part.
The first question, do you think the military should give a readjustment period to vets with what you've experienced?
Yes, definitely.
And then the other thing he said, he too expressed that he had absolutely zero problems with the anti-war protesters.
The people that he had a problem with were those who did not acknowledge Vietnam.
Who didn't even care.
Exactly.
That's basically what I was saying.
What hurt me and upset me more were the people that didn't even care, you know.
And there was a lot of them.
And they just seemed to have no feelings one way or another.
You say, hey, I went to Nam, you know, and they say, oh, really?
Big deal.
You know, I would rather a guy say, oh, man, that was terrible.
You shouldn't have gone or, you know, Vietnam was a waste of time or a baby killer or anything, you know, that sort of thing, rather than say, I don't care.

you know, at least the protesters had a voice, they had an opinion, you know, they used it, you know, so, you know, from that standpoint, the ones that I agree 100% with what the, you know, the pilot said, you know, the ones that didn't acknowledge it at all, to me, are the worst, you know, because it was a situation where, granted, they weren't, our country wasn't on the line, you know, they weren't invading America or United States or anything like that, but

American lives and money was being lost and thrown away basically on a daily basis You know and that affects everybody You will for many many many years I want to get back to Vietnam and with the units the one last question that I had I was sort of sidetracked from but I wanted you to elaborate a little bit more on the racism and
Was it mainly whites versus black or blacks versus everybody?
It was pretty much the blacks did their own thing.
And they really, I would say, you know, probably I'd say 80% of the soldiers were black.
Okay.
And so leaders were mostly sergeants were black.
Very few officers were black because you had to be educated to be an officer.
And not that blacks are not educated by any means.
The majority of them just were not college people.
And the college blacks were smart enough not to get drafted or go in the Army.
So, you know, if they were smart enough to be smart, they didn't go in the service.
So very few blacks were actually officers.

so you had a direct conflict of race right there and the blacks had their own clicks and their own things and you know they get together and you know you tell them to go out on a mission or something and they just look at you and say you know where you can jump you know that sort of thing and just say i'm not going to do it and you know and here's a lieutenant cherry lieutenant trying to tell this black guy that stands three foot tall on him to go out and run this ambush you know and
It just didn't happen, so there was a lot of that.
And, I mean, you really would be fear of them.
I mean, you would fear your life from your fellow soldier, you know, buddy.
And if you didn't get in good with them, you know, you never knew whether they were going to shoot you in the back or frag you or what.
And, I mean, we'd get in a firefight, and, you know, if you pissed one of them off, I mean, you better be looking over your shoulder to make sure he wasn't behind you because you might get shot.
And it did happen.
I mean, you know, guys would get shot all the time in a firefight, you know.
And it was the racism.
It was more racism than anything else.
You know, if you didn't work with them, you know, if you were anti-black or anti-Hispanic or had any views or opinions about their racism, you know, generally you wouldn't last.
You had to go with the flow and, you know, be one of the guys and this sort of thing.
And there again...
The longer you were around them, the longer you were in country, the better you had a chance of living, not only from your people, but from the other ones too, you know.
And the blacks were the most prominent.
Of course, the Hispanic people had that type of thing.
And there was, I guess there was a few of the actual Vietnamese or chinks or whatever you want to call them that were there in the service too with us that worked with us.
We called them, what did we call those guys?
I can't even remember the name of them, but they were like the Vietnamese scouts guys that worked with us, you know, local villager type thing.
But they were actually Army.
I mean, I don't know how they, you know, they weren't Arvin.
They were our guys.
They were basically employed by the U.S. government as scouts, kind of like Kit Carson and Tonto or whatever, you know, that way.
So, you know, from that standpoint.
But, you know, we would.
And some of the times we'd go out, we'd actually have, they called them Kit Carson Scouts.
That was the name.
They called them Kit Carson Scouts.
They would go out with us and work with us and stuff like that.
But the blacks were the biggest racial thing.
And they had their cliques and their things.
And, you know, they had their prostitute rings they ran.
They had black market food and drugs and liquor.
You know, liquor was very prominent.
And, you know, you get it for almost nothing.
But, I mean, yeah.
We, I remember one time, we wanted some beer in the field.
I'll never forget this.
We were in the middle of nowhere.
I mean, there was no fire bases around, nothing.
And we had this one black sergeant that was, he was really a cool guy.
And he called back in and he says, my men need some beer.
And the supply sergeant at the fire base says, you know, they got on the radio and back and forth, back and forth.
And it wasn't two hours later, here comes a chopper with a pallet full of beer.
I mean, it was a whole pallet of cases of beer.
And we had a whole company of guys out there, so there was quite a few guys.
And they set this pallet of hot beer down, and they set it down and left.
I mean, they didn't hang around at all.
And we all went out there and packed up as much beer as we could possibly put on our bodies and carried it with us.
So we had beer out there, and the jungle was black labeled, too.
I'll never forget it.
It's the worst tasting beer, but it was beer.
And we would take it in the mountains, and the streams were real cool.
And we'd take and put it in the stream and try to cool it down a little bit and, you know, then drink it.
But I'll never forget that.
I mean, you know, those guys, they could work deals on stuff.
And, you know, if we needed a particular, you know, weapon or something like that out there, you know, a lot of times, you know,

Especially when we were in the small groups of special force type thing, you know, when the first calve, we would use AKs and shoot those because if we were out there and had an ambush and we started shooting M16s, the enemy would know we would be there.
Whereas if we were shooting AKs, it would sound just like them, so they really wouldn't know any different.
So we would always get extra rounds and stuff like that from those guys.
You know, we could always pick up stuff from the black market anywhere
to get the AKs and stuff like that, we were able to pick up enemy weapons and extra rounds.
Did you have to go through black guys to get the AKs?
Usually, yeah.
Wow, I didn't realize that they had controlled so much of the black market.
They did.
There again, it wasn't everywhere, but if you wanted something, you knew you could go get it if you had the money to pay for it.
Well, on the black market, were there also Claymore mines?
Yeah, you could get anything just about.
on the black market.
You know, those guys, BC's could, yeah, they could buy it too, I'm sure.
I mean, those guys, they had everything we had.
So, from that standpoint, you know, we never knew who the real enemy was, so to speak, you know.
Right, exactly.
So, you know, it's a situation, you know, they always, you know, they had a good supply of stuff as we did, and that goes back to the Arvins, where we supplied them in that fire base, and
A week later, they overran the fire base and took everything we gave them.
So we knew the enemy had all the mines and cannons and bullets and everything.
I mean, here we were getting shot at us with our own stuff because the Arvins let them have it.
Well, that leads to some general questions.
And do you think that the U.S. could have ever won that war?
I really do.
The way they fought it, or maybe if they...

the thing that it would have taken it probably would have killed more civilians than it did but it would have killed less people overall and it would have taken a lot less years but they should have gone in with massive strikes and massive overruns and just basically just marched through the whole country and took it away from them and they could have done that because they knew where the enemy was
But the enemy would set up in villages.
They'd set up in near villages.
And if they went in with an airstrike, they always took the chance of killing the villagers and killing the friendlies, and they didn't want to do that.
So then they did the hit-and-miss type thing, and it took years and years and years, and nobody ever won.
Or at least we sure didn't.
But I personally feel if they would have gone in with massive strikes...
They could have overtaken it, and it would have cost some lives, but it would have saved more than it cost.
And that's just from what I saw from the intelligence part of it.
Of course, my first six months in country, I knew nothing about this because I was just an infantry soldier doing what I was told.

But after I got into the intelligence part and saw that they actually knew where the enemy was, they knew how much enemy was out there, they knew where they were going and what they were doing, all they had to do was go in there and wipe them out.
And, yeah, that's what, you know, our intelligence was far superior to theirs.
Speaking of intelligence, supposedly from around 65 to 68, the military intelligence put the enemy's strength at less than 300,000, while the CIA at that time put it at twice that.
I think the 300,000 is a very realistic number.
Wow.
Because there wasn't that many there.
The numbers weren't there.
What was the enemy's strength in 70?
Well, I'm going to say probably it was closer down to the 100,000 mark, somewhere in that range.
The numbers just weren't there at all.
They had pulled back into Cambodia.
They were back into North Vietnam.
There was not that many
troops in South Vietnam at the time.
And the ones that were there were just in small areas and small companies and stuff.
So it wasn't a major masses of companies and battalions and stuff like that.
So yeah, it was spread out over the whole country, but it wasn't the numbers in the area from that standpoint.
Do you think we belong to Vietnam to begin with?
Do you think there was an actual cause that was worth fighting for?
I think so.
And I think the people in the upper government, of course, anything you can do to promote freedom, democracy, whatever, for anybody, to give them a chance to stand on their own is worth a cause.
The loss of lives and the loss of money, equipment, everything, that's hard to justify that.
I mean, there again, the way it was gone about was probably wrong.
I don't think there will ever be another conflict like that because they learned from it.
But you look at, like, France and Germany nowadays and what went through World War I and World War II.
And Korea.
Korea still is having major conflicts, but they do have a free government.
And so, I mean, they had those going on, so they said, why not Vietnam, too?
Give them a chance.
So I think the idea and the concept was good.
It just was not properly carried out.
What was your concept at the Vietnam government?
What did you know about the... Not a whole lot.
I didn't really get any of the major cities or major government whatsoever, you know, because we were almost all the way out.
What little reading I did do about it, you know,
They basically wanted stuff, but their economy was so poor and so, you know, I don't know, diluted, whatever the proper term is, that it could not properly be carried out.
And the rich had rich and the poor were poor, but there was no in-between.
And so, therefore, the economy part of it was very, very, you know,
There was 99% poor people and 1% rich people type thing.
And they needed a major turnaround in their economy.
And I guess the poor just didn't care.
I mean, they had their little village and their little rice paddy and did their farming, and they could care less about the rest of the world.
And here comes these guys, and they're shooting everybody up.
You know, what the hell are you doing in my village in the middle of nowhere?
They could care less.
So, you know, the city's...
Saigon, you know, the major cities, they really needed to be, you know, saved, so to speak.
But the villagers, they were perfectly happy.
They could care less.
And they're the ones that really suffered more in the cities because the cities were pretty secure.
So, you know, it's really a weird thing.
It's kind of a, you know, catch-22 type thing.
You damn if you do and you damn if you don't type deal.
What do you think the military...
or we as Americans have learned anything?
I think so.
Do you think the military has learned?
Well, the Goddard Granada incident, for example, just recently.
They went in full bore, came in with a lot of force, took the island, secured it.
Bam, they're there.
If they would have done that in Vietnam, it wouldn't have went on forever.
From day one.
Day one.
So, I mean, military training...
needs to be updated, which it probably has been since then.
And I think they spent a lot more money on the military since then.
At the same time, they learned from their mistakes.
They know what they need to do.
And the president obviously has spent lots and lots and lots of money trying to keep it up.
So I think because of that, they will not make the same mistake of going in in a fashion of not
overrunning and taking, and they're not going to take anything off anybody anymore.
And I think they took too much off the North Vietnamese, if you know what I mean.
They just sit back and were passive rather than active.
And I think you'll see if there is another war ever, it'll be a very active war.
It'll be a short run, bam, bam, it'll be over type thing.
Oh, what are your general views about Vietnamese before and after it?
Before, I had no view at all because I really didn't know any.
I personally, at this time, don't.
I don't know.
I still don't like them because, you know, this is just a general type thing.
I don't know any personally, although when they first started filtering in to here, you know, especially in the fishing villages and stuff like that and shrimping and stuff,
I really had a real bad taste in my mouth for them.
Not that I wanted to go kill any of them or anything like that, but I didn't think they belonged here.
But at the same time, you think we didn't belong over there either.
So if they're willing to work and have a living and support themselves, I really can't argue with it.
But I felt our government gave them too much.
Their subsidies and stuff like that, they brought them here, they put them in business, they paid them to work.
You know, they supported them, and I think we subsidized them way, way too far.
And, I mean, there's a lot of... You think we subsidized them too far in Vietnam, maybe, too?
Possibly.
Okay.
Very possibly.
There's a lot of Vietnamese that are better off than Americans because of the government.
If the government would subsidize some of these guys out here, the farmers and stuff like that, they'd be back on their feet, too.
So, you know, it's kind of a weird situation.
So I've kind of got a bitter taste...

form in all honesty not that I know any of them personally or anything personal grudges or anything like that but I just you see one and all you think about is war and you know so from that standpoint it's really tough to like them did you ever consider them a second class citizen when you were in Vietnam no not at all ever look down on them no no I never that never even mattered I mean they were
You know, they're human beings.
They're the same level.
Everybody's human.
You know, there's no upper or lower class.
There was richer and poorer, but nobody was second class.
You know, everybody was equal.
Even though they didn't have the modern facilities we have.
They were nice.
Some of them, you know, that we did get to know and meet were just super people.
I mean, you know, especially in the outer line villages in the middle of nowhere.
I mean, you walk up on, you know, a village and come in there and,
You know, they'd greet you and they'd feed you and they'd be nice and helpful and friendly and, you know, number one GI, you know, this sort of thing.
And, you know, you were the greatest person in the world.
And, you know, they'd mama sign, you know, papa sign, you know, here, you want some food, you know, this sort of thing.
And the super people, you know, in all honesty.
But they didn't want to be bothered.
They were happy with their lives.
And you can't blame them, you know.
And at the same time, they would take anything you'd give them, too.
They wanted chocolate or cigarettes or whatever.
Gum.
Gum.
You could always win their ways with them.
